[2] UK (Scotland)
Date: Fri 26 Apr 2013
Source: STV, local [abbreviated & edited]
http://local.stv.tv/edinburgh/magazine/222902-measles-outbreak-in-wales-and-england-sparks-call-for-mmr-immunisation/


New surge in measles outbreak sparks call for Scots to be immunised
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Health chiefs in Scotland are urging parents to get their children vaccinated against measles after the number of cases south of the Border soared past 1500. Scottish health boards say they have so far avoided any significant outbreaks of the potentially deadly condition with just 16 cases recorded across the country. But with cases still spreading in England and Wales ahead of the forthcoming exam period and school holidays medics say there is no room for complacency in trying to contain the situation.

Health experts in Wales are preparing to enter their 3rd week of holding MMR clinics at schools and children are being urged to get immunised before their exams begin. The number of people that have contracted the disease in the south-west of
the country [Wales} now stands at 942 with some 83 people being admitted to hospital since the outbreak began.

On Thursday [25 Apr 2013] Chief Medical Officer Sir Harry Burns announced older children in Scotland were being offered the MMR vaccine. Uptake rate for the MMR vaccine in Scotland currently remains above the World Health Organisation's target of 95 percent with 97.1 percent of children vaccinated before they reach their 5th birthday. Wales is also hitting this 95 percent target. England is just below it at 94 percent.

Even so, there have been 16 laboratory confirmed cases in Scotland since the start of the year, a figure Health Protection Scotland says might indicate that the outbreaks in England and Wales are unlikely to be mirrored on a similar scale in Scotland. Dr Kevin Pollock, senior epidemiologist and research lead at Health Protection Scotland said: "In Wales, their vaccine uptake in those under the age one is similar to Scotland. "The problem is not the uptake rate of the younger children at the moment. "It is instead those children who didn't get the MMR vaccine over a decade ago when the parents decided that they didn't want to get that vaccine.
"In Wales, between 2000 to 2002, the MMR vaccination uptake rate was 70 percent. During the same time period in Scotland, this was 87 percent. "This was partly based on Wakefield's study and also because in Swansea, there was a local media campaign against the vaccine which had a big effect on the uptake. "The risks in Scotland are therefore much lower."

Around 18 months ago, children between 10 & 17 in Scotland were given a further chance to have the MMR vaccination in schools when the Secondary 3 booster was offered. In light of the outbreaks in England and Wales, NHS boards across the
country will now write to parents of all unvaccinated or partially vaccinated children aged 10 to 17 with an invitation to attend for vaccination over the next few weeks. Strongly supporting the plea, NHS 24 medical director Professor Crooks said: "Measles is not a minor condition of childhood that only causes a rash. "It is potentially serious and occasionally tragically fatal condition. Immunisation protects people against measles but you have to have the full course, one injection is not enough."

