[3] UK (Wales): 1st fatality
Date: Tue 23 Apr 2023
Source: The Daily Post [edited]
http://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/health/measles-outbreak-could-hit-1000-2995491

Measles outbreak could hit 1000 at its peak, warn doctors
---------------------------------------------------------
Measles cases were expected to show another rise today [Tue 23 Apr 2023], when health officials announce the latest figures revealing the scale of the outbreak in Wales. Officials warned the outbreak could soon become the biggest in UK and Ireland for a generation, and may hit 1000 cases by the time it peaks. Shadow Health Minister Darrren Millar last night called on parents throughout North Wales to listen to public health professionals. There are over 10 000 children who are not fully protected by the vaccine in the Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board area and at risk of contracting measles. Mr Millar said: "This is a very serious situation as although the outbreak has centred on the Swansea area, cases have been detected across Wales." Clinics will be held at 10 schools in the Abertawe Bro Morgannwg University Health Board (ABMU) area throughout this week while Cwm Taf Health Board will be visiting 3 schools in the region.

Health officials at Cardiff and Vale University Health Board (UHB) also held top-level meetings yesterday to thrash out a vaccination programme for schools in its area. A spokesman for the board urged parents to sign and return consent forms for unvaccinated children to get their jabs as soon as possible.

1st fatality
------------
Meanwhile, the results of a post mortem examination on a man found dead at his Swansea home on Thursday morning are expected later this week. Gareth Colfer-Williams, 25, was suffering from measles when he died, and is the 1st fatality to be linked with the disease. Last week the epidemic, which is centred on the Swansea area, reached 808, with 20 new cases being seen every day. Latest figures are due to be released by Public Health Wales (PHW) on Tuesday and are expected to show a significant rise as the outbreak continues to show no signs of slowing down.

Officials have warned that it is now at risk of becoming the biggest outbreak in the UK and Ireland since the introduction of the MMR in 1988. The largest outbreak was seen in 1999-2000 when 1200 people were affected in Dublin and 3 died. A PHW spokeswoman said: "We are definitely expecting to reach 1000 cases as we are seeing 20 new cases a day, which will take us up to around 950 by the end of next week."

